==Reception==
===Arcade version===
In the United States, it was among the thirteen highest-grossing [[1983 in video games|arcade games of 1983]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=AMOA Votes On Annual Game Awards |magazine=[[Cash Box]] |date=October 29, 1983 |page=60 |url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox45unse_20/page/68}}</ref> In Japan, ''Game Machine'' listed ''Zoom 909'' on their June 1, 1985 issue as being the thirteenth most-successful upright/cockpit arcade unit of the month.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - アップライト, コックピット型TVゲーム機 (Upright/Cockpit Videos)|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=261|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=1 June 1985|page=23|lang=ja}}</ref>

The arcade game received positive reviews from critics. American magazine ''Video Games'' gave it a highly positive review following its AMOA 1982 debut, ranking it the second best game of the show. They called it a "gorgeous, 3-D game that deserves the" moniker "Space [[Turbo (video game)|Turbo]]" with "high-quality graphics" and "fast and furious" action.<ref name="VideoGames">{{cite magazine | magazine = Video Games | volume = 1 | publisher = Pumpkin Press | issue = 7 | page = 66 | title = Top Ten Hits | date=March 1983 | url=https://archive.org/stream/Video_Games_Volume_1_Number_06_1983-03_Pumpkin_Press_US#page/n65/mode/2up}}</ref>

French magazine ''[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]]'', in its May 1983 issue, rated the arcade game six out of six stars.<ref name="Tilt">{{cite magazine |title=Service Compris Arcade: Les Seuers Froides |magazine=[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]] |date=May 16, 1983 |issue=5 |pages=72–3 |lang=fr |url=https://archive.org/details/Tilt005/page/n71/mode/2up |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> British magazine ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' also gave it a positive review, noting the behind-the-ship perspective, comparing the opening tunnel section to the [[Death Star]] battle in the film ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' (1977), and stating that anyone "who has enjoyed the" ''Buck Rogers'' "TV series will be interested to see just how it converts to the video screen!"<ref name="CVG">{{cite magazine |title=Arcade Action |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=16 June 1983 |issue=21 (July 1983) |pages=30–1 |url=https://www.solvalou.com/arcade/reviews/178/500}}</ref>

===Home conversions===
Michael Blanchet for ''[[Electronic Fun with Computers & Games]]'' reviewed the Coleco Adam version, stating: "After playing ''Buck Rogers'' a scant fifty times, I noticed an ever-increasing number of on-screen glitches. I can only presume they were caused by tape wear".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Electronic_Fun_with_Computer_Games_Vol_02_No_05_1984-03_Fun_Games_Publishing_US/page/n51/mode/2up|title=Electronic Fun with Computer & Games - Vol 02 No 05 (1984-03)(Fun & Games Publishing)(US)|date=March 16, 1984|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

Dan Hallassey for ''[[Ahoy!]]'' reviewed the Commodore 64 and VIC-20 versions, stating that "graphics and gameplay combine to make this an excellent and absorbing – though admittedly one-note – space game".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/ahoy-magazine-03/page/n55/mode/2up|title=Ahoy! Magazine Issue 03|date=March 16, 1984|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

